From Raw Data to Business Insights

Author

Dr Aniruddha Bonnerjee

Abstract
Session 2: Learning some useful formulas for data analytics

Session 2: Excel Formulas + Table Lookups

Duration: 2 hours

Session Objective

From cleaning the transition to data analytics. By the end of this session, you will be able to: - Apply essential Excel functions (IF, SUMIF, COUNTIF, AVERAGEIF) to analyze data - Understand the logic and power of table lookups - Use VLOOKUP to retrieve data from reference tables - Use XLOOKUP as a modern, more flexible alternative - Enrich your dataset by combining data from multiple sources - Calculate derived metrics like profit margins - Build comprehensive summary analysis tables

Why Formulas and Lookups Matter

In Session 1, you cleaned your data. But clean data alone doesnât answer business questions. You need to: - Calculate totals by category (SUMIF) - Count occurrences (COUNTIF) - Find averages (AVERAGEIF) - Connect related data (VLOOKUP/XLOOKUP)

Todayâs mindset: Transform from data cleaner to data analyst. Youâre not just organizing informationâyouâre extracting insights.

Part 1: Conditional Calculations (60 minutes)

In Part 1 we will begin the journey towards data analysis. For this we will be introducing some new functions. First we use the UNIQUE function to generate unique lists for State, Product Line, Sales Channel and Customer Segment. Next we will use the SUMIF (first) and AVERAGEIF (second) to derive sums and averages of Sales and Targets.

  1. First create a new sheet by clicking on the + icon to generate a new empty data sheet. Your workbook will now have three sheets: the original data, cleaned data and this new sheet you created.

  2. Rename the new sheet Summary Analysis by right clicking on the sheet name in the bottom.

UNIQUE: Unique Values

What it does: Gives a list of UNIQUE values in a column.

Syntax:

=UNIQUE(range_to_check)

Go to cell A1 in the new summary analysis sheet. Type the following formula.

=UNIQUE('Clean Data'!B:.B)

This will list the 8 States in order of appearance in the clean data (West Bengal to Gujarat) in cells A2:A9 with the column heading State in cell A1.

Tip

Since State is also contained in Column B of Clean Data and it appears first, the column header is already typed out. You donât need to enter it manually.

Important

Note that since we are working in a new sheet, we must tell Excel where to find the cell references we want to use in our formula. In this case it is in Clean Data. Notice the pointer syntax carefully.

SUMIF: Conditional Totals

What it does: Adds up numbers that meet a specific condition.

Syntax:

=SUMIF(range_to_check, condition, range_to_sum)

Mental Model: âLook in this range, find cells matching this condition, then sum the corresponding values from another range.â

Example 1: Total Sales & Targets by State

Step 1: Create the structure by using SUMIF function. We have already generated a list of States by using the UNIQUE function in A1. Type Total Sales in B1 and Total Target in C1. Then use the following SUMIF formula for Total Sales and Total Target Columns. Note, you only need to do it for the first occurrence and copy. The formulas are shown below:

State (A1) Total Sales (B1) Total Target (C1)
Karnataka (A2) =SUMIF(âClean Dataâ!B:.B, A2, âClean Dataâ!F:.F) =SUMIF(âClean Dataâ!B:.B, A2, âClean Dataâ!G:.G)

Tip

Note the use of the . sign. This locks the column and prevents spill-overs. Many people also use the $ sign. For example instead of B:.B, use $B:$B as the column range in Excel. Explanation of the formulas:

Translation: - âClean Dataâ!B:B â Look in Clean Data sheet column B (State) - value in A2 (State Value)â Find all A2 entries entries - âClean Dataâ!F:.Fâ Sum corresponding values in Clean Data column F (Sales)

COUNTIF: Conditional Counting

What it does: Counts how many cells meet a specific condition.

Syntax:

=COUNTIF(range_to_check, condition)

Formula:

This formula tells Excel to go to âClean Dataâ and count all occurrences of the cell belonging to A2 (Karnataka). Drag this formula down for all States. Your expanded State summary table should now look like this:

Example 3: How Many Transactions Met Target overall?

You created the Performance column in Part 1 using the IF function, where we assigned a value of 1 if Target was met and 0 otherwise. This data is in column L of Clean Data sheet. Go to cell A18 in the Summary Analysis Sheet and type Target Met to give it context. Next go to cell B18 (next to it) and type the formula below:

Formula:

=COUNTIF('Clean Data'!L:.L, 1)

This tells Excel to go to column L in sheet âClean Dataâ and count all occurrences of 1 (where sales has met target).

Tip

An alternative and clever way to do it would be just to sum the entries in Performance Column since they only consist of 0 and 1. Formula:

=SUM('Clean Data'!L:.L)

In both cases the answer should be 243. What can we infer from this?

Out of 1000 data rows, sales were met only for 243 rows (i.e, 24.3%). 
Either sales performance needs to improve or the targets are unrealistic.

AVERAGEIF: Conditional Averages

What it does: Calculates the average of numbers that meet a specific condition.

Syntax:

=AVERAGEIF(range_to_check, condition, range_to_average)

  • Type the header Average Sales in Cell B20. Then in Cell B21 use the AVERAGEIF formula shown below and copy the formula to all Customer Segments.

Part 2: Introduction to Table Lookups (30 minutes)

The Problem Lookups Solve

Your sales data has Product Line, but you need: - Product Category - Profit Margin %

This information exists in a separate Product Master table.

Old way: Manually copy-paste for 940 rows (error-prone, time-consuming, not sustainable)
Smart way: Use Lookups to automatically retrieve the data

Understanding Lookup Logic

Analogy: Phone Directory

You have: Personâs name
You want: Their phone number
You do: Look up name in directory, retrieve corresponding number

In Excel:

You have: Product Line (e.g., âElectronicsâ)
You want: Profit Margin % (e.g., 25%) or Product Category (e.g, Technology)
You do: Look up âElectronicsâ in Product Master, retrieve corresponding Profit Margin

VLOOKUP Syntax

=VLOOKUP(lookup_value, table_array, col_index_num, [range_lookup])

Parameters explained:

  1. lookup_value: What youâre searching for
    • Example: E2 (cell containing âSports & Fitnessâ)
  2. table_array: Where to search
    • Example: ProductMaster!$A$1:$D$6 (the entire Product Master table)
  3. col_index_num: Which column to return (counting from left)
    • Column 1 = Product Line
    • Column 2 = Product Code
    • Column 3 = Product Category â We want this!
    • Column 4 = Profit Margin %
  4. range_lookup: FALSE for exact match
    • Always use FALSE for business data!
    • TRUE is for approximate matches (rarely used)
Caution

Remember to use $ signs in your lookup reference otherwise you will run into a spill error.

Product Master Table Structure

Letâs visualize this clearly. Open the Excel file ProductMaster.xlsx. You will see the following data. It contains a few rows and columns, some of which are not present in our original data file. Our goal is to add some information from here to our Clean Data Sheet.

Example 1: Retrieve Product Category

Goal: Add a âProduct_Categoryâ column to your sales data

Step 1: Insert a new column - Go to column O and in cell O1 type Product Category. We will next use VLOOKUP to retrieve the Product Category from the Excel file ProductMaster.xlsx. Note that Product_Category is in column 3 in product_master_table worksheet.

Step 2: Write the VLOOKUP formula in O2.

Product_Line is in column E in the original data file (Clean Data worksheet):

=VLOOKUP(E2,[ProductMaster.xlsx]product_master_table!$A$1:$D$6,3, FALSE)

Step 3: Understand each part - E2 â Look for this value (the Product Line in current row) -[ProductMaster.xlsx]product_master_table â Search in this file (ProductMaster) and in the worksheet product_master_table, using columns from $A$2:$D$6 - 3 â Return value from 3rd column (Product_Category) - FALSE â Exact match only

Step 4: Copy down - Double-click fill handle to copy formula to all rows

Result: If D2 = âElectronicsâ, the formula returns âTechnologyâ

Example 2: Retrieve Profit Margin

Goal: Add a âProfit Marginâ column by going to Column P in Clean Data and type it in the header (P1). In P2 type the following formula:

Formula:

=VLOOKUP(E2,[ProductMaster.xlsx]product_master_table!$A$1:$D$6, 4, FALSE)

Breakdown: - Same lookup value (E2) and product_master_table - 4 â Return value from 4th column (Profit_Margin_%) - Result: If E2 = âSports & Fitnessâ, returns 30.

Why Use $ Signs (Absolute References)?

The $ signs lock the table range when you copy the formula down:

Without $ signs: - Row 2: Looks in A:D â - Row 3: Looks in A:D shifted down â (wrong!)

With $ signs: - Row 2: Looks in \(A:\)D â - Row 3: Still looks in \(A:\)D â (correct!) - Row 100: Still looks in \(A:\)D â (correct!)

Rule of thumb: Always use $ for the table_array in VLOOKUP.

Testing Your VLOOKUP

After creating your VLOOKUP formulas, verify they work:

  1. Pick a specific row (e.g., row 10)
  2. Note the Product_Line (e.g., âApparelâ)
  3. Check the Product Master table - What should Apparel return?
    • Product_Category: âFashionâ
    • Profit_Margin_%: 40
  4. Check your formula result - Does it match?

Do this for 3-4 rows to ensure accuracy!

XLOOKUP - Modern Approach

Why XLOOKUP is Better Than VLOOKUP

VLOOKUP has limitations: 1. Can only look to the right - Column order matters, so Product Line HAS to be the FIRST column of the lookup table 2. Hard-to-read syntax - Column counting is manual and error-prone 3. No built-in error handling 4. Table must be sorted for approximate matches

XLOOKUP (available in Excel 365/2021+) fixes all of this!

XLOOKUP Syntax

=XLOOKUP(lookup_value, lookup_array, return_array, [if_not_found])

Much simpler! Only 3-4 parameters instead of 4!

  1. lookup_value: What youâre searching for
  2. lookup_array: Where to search (just one column!)
  3. return_array: What to return (just one column!)
  4. if_not_found: (Optional) What to show if not found

Example 1: Retrieve Product Category with XLOOKUP

Formula:

=XLOOKUP(E2, [ProductMaster.xlsx]product_master_table!$A$1:$A$6, [ProductMaster.xlsx]product_master_table!$C$1:$C$6, "Not Found")

Translation: - Look for value in E2 (e.g., âElectronicsâ) - Search in column A of ProductMaster (Product_Line column) - Return corresponding value from column C (Product_Category) - If not found, display âNot Foundâ

XLOOKUP advantages: - â Clearer (no column counting!) - â Built-in error handling - â Can look left or right (order doesnât matter!)

Example 2: Retrieve Profit Margin with XLOOKUP

Formula:

=XLOOKUP(E2, [ProductMaster.xlsx]product_master_table!$A$1:$A$6, [ProductMaster.xlsx]product_master_table!$D$1:$D$6, "Not Found")

Translation: - Look for value in E2 - Search in column A (Product_Line) - Return value from column D (Profit_Margin_%) - If not found, return âNot Foundâ

Common Mistakes to Avoid

â Forgetting $ signs in lookup table references - Bad: =VLOOKUP(D2, ProductMaster!A:D, 3, FALSE) - Good: =VLOOKUP(D2, ProductMaster!$A:$D, 3, FALSE)

â Using hard-coded values instead of cell references - Bad: =SUMIF(B:B, "Maharashtra", E:E) (what if you want to change the state?) - Better: =SUMIF($B:$B, A2, $E:$E) (flexible, reusable)

â Mixing up column numbers in VLOOKUP - Count carefully! Column A=1, B=2, C=3, D=4

â Not verifying formulas before copying - Always test on first row before copying to 1000 rows!

Key Takeaways

â Conditional functions (SUMIF, COUNTIF, AVERAGEIF) turn raw data into insights - Theyâre your bread and butter for analysis

â Lookups connect related data - VLOOKUP/XLOOKUP let you combine information from multiple sources

â One dataset + Reference tables = Enriched analysis - This is how professional analysts work

â Formula mastery = Efficiency - Write once, copy thousands of times

â Always test your formulas - Check a few rows manually before trusting them

â XLOOKUP is the future - If you have it, use it! If not, VLOOKUP still works great
